✅ Flow of Application
Client → Controller → Service → Repository → Data

1. Model (Data Class)
📁 model/User.java

package com.example.bottleapp.model;

public class User {

    private int id;
    private String name;

    public User(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }

    public void setId(int id) { this.id = id; }
    public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }
}

Why Model?
👉 Represents data structure
👉 Used in API input/output

🔹 2. Repository (Data Layer)
📁 repository/UserRepository.java
package com.example.bottleapp.repository;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;
import com.example.bottleapp.model.User;
import java.util.*;

@Repository
public class UserRepository {

    private List<User> users = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<User> findAll() {
        return users;
    }

    public String save(User user) {
        users.add(user);
        return "User saved";
    }
}

✅ Why @Repository?
✔ Handles data
✔ In real apps → connects to DB

3. Service (Business Logic)
📁 service/UserService.java

package com.example.bottleapp.service;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import com.example.bottleapp.repository.UserRepository;
import com.example.bottleapp.model.User;
import java.util.*;

@Service
public class UserService {

    @Autowired
    private UserRepository repository;

    public List<User> getUsers() {
        return repository.findAll();
    }

    public String createUser(User user) {
        return repository.save(user);
    }

    public String updateUser(int id) {
        return "User updated: " + id;
    }

    public String deleteUser(int id) {
        return "User deleted: " + id;
    }
}

✅ Why @Service?
✔ Contains logic
✔ Keeps controller simple

✅ Why @Autowired?
👉 Spring automatically injects object
❌ No need:
new UserRepository();

✅ This is Dependency Injection

🔹 4. Controller (API Layer)
📁 controller/UserController.java

package com.example.bottleapp.controller;

import org.springframework.webapp.service.UserService;import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import com.example.bottleapp.model.User;
import java.util.*;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @Autowired
    private UserService service;

    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getUsers() {
        return service.getUsers();
    }

    @PostMapping
    public String createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return service.createUser(user);
    }

    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public String updateUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return service.updateUser(id);
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return service.deleteUser(id);
    }
}
``
